00:02:04.991 --> 00:02:07.793
Please join me in
welcoming Noam Chomsky.

00:02:07.894 --> 00:02:10.797
[applause]

00:02:24.877 --> 00:02:28.480
NOAM CHOMSKY: First question,
as always, is can you hear me?

00:02:28.581 --> 00:02:30.616
Yeah, OK.

00:02:30.716 --> 00:02:34.220
For quite a few years,
I've been intrigued

00:02:34.320 --> 00:02:37.223
by an interesting
debate that took place

00:02:37.323 --> 00:02:44.363
about 25 years ago between
two great scientists, Carl

00:02:44.463 --> 00:02:47.500
Sagan, Ernst Mayr.

00:02:47.600 --> 00:02:50.670
They were discussing
the likelihood

00:02:50.770 --> 00:02:57.343
of finding extraterrestrial
intelligent life.

00:02:57.443 --> 00:02:59.612
And Sagan, who looked at
it from the point of view

00:02:59.712 --> 00:03:04.717
of an astrophysicist,
calculated the number of planets

00:03:04.817 --> 00:03:08.454
more or less like Earth and
concluded that the chances

00:03:08.554 --> 00:03:10.522
are quite high.

00:03:10.622 --> 00:03:14.193
Mayr, looking at
it as a biologist,

00:03:14.293 --> 00:03:19.298
said, look, we have
only one test case,

00:03:19.398 --> 00:03:24.036
namely Earth, which has had
about 50 billion species.

00:03:24.136 --> 00:03:28.540
And we can raise
the question what

00:03:28.640 --> 00:03:32.845
are the criteria for
biological success

00:03:32.946 --> 00:03:37.717
on Earth, with 50
billion cases to look at.

00:03:37.817 --> 00:03:42.321
And he pointed out that there
is a striking regularity.

00:03:42.421 --> 00:03:47.493
The species that are successful,
a lot of them around,

00:03:47.593 --> 00:03:53.032
basically, are those that
mutate quickly like bacteria,

00:03:53.132 --> 00:03:56.969
or those that have a
fixed niche like beetles,

00:03:57.070 --> 00:04:00.072
and they just stay there
no matter what happens.

00:04:00.172 --> 00:04:04.110
And as you move up the scale
of what we call intelligence,

00:04:04.210 --> 00:04:06.879
biological success declines.

00:04:06.979 --> 00:04:09.048
So there are not many mammals.

00:04:09.148 --> 00:04:12.051
There are very few apes.

00:04:12.151 --> 00:04:13.752
The only reason
there's a lot of cows

00:04:13.852 --> 00:04:16.188
is because we domesticate them.

00:04:16.288 --> 00:04:19.892
But by and large,
biological success

00:04:19.992 --> 00:04:23.929
declines as
intelligence increases.

00:04:24.029 --> 00:04:28.834
Humans look like an exception,
but that's a statistical blip--

00:04:28.934 --> 00:04:33.172
just a tiny moment of
evolutionary time--

00:04:33.272 --> 00:04:36.408
last couple thousand
years, actually.

00:04:36.508 --> 00:04:40.078
So his conclusion is
that, I'll quote him,

00:04:40.179 --> 00:04:44.049
"The history of life on
Earth refutes the claim

00:04:44.149 --> 00:04:48.587
that it is better to be
smart than to be stupid."

00:04:48.687 --> 00:04:50.790
What it shows, in fact,
is it's much better

00:04:50.890 --> 00:04:53.126
to be stupid than smart.

00:04:53.226 --> 00:04:54.760
That's the conclusion.

00:04:54.860 --> 00:04:59.532
He also points out that the
average lifespan of a species

00:04:59.632 --> 00:05:01.867
is about 100,000 years.

00:05:01.967 --> 00:05:03.969
We've doubled it.

00:05:04.069 --> 00:05:06.205
We're about 200,000,
and so we're

00:05:06.305 --> 00:05:10.309
a little beyond the
expected extinction point.

00:05:10.409 --> 00:05:14.213
Well, that's the question
I want to consider today.

00:05:14.313 --> 00:05:17.583
Is it better to be
smart than stupid?

00:05:17.683 --> 00:05:22.287
It was addressed recently by
a very good Indian writer.

00:05:22.387 --> 00:05:27.326
Amitav Ghosh has a book called
The Great Derangement, Climate

00:05:27.426 --> 00:05:30.330
Change and the Unthinkable.

00:05:30.430 --> 00:05:35.134
And in fact, our failure
to address the most awesome

00:05:35.234 --> 00:05:38.103
challenge of human history--

00:05:38.203 --> 00:05:41.107
with the possible exception
of nuclear weapons--

00:05:41.207 --> 00:05:46.079
is indeed a true derangement,
and painful evidence

00:05:46.179 --> 00:05:49.915
for the plausibility
of Mayr's thesis

00:05:50.015 --> 00:05:53.385
that it's better to
be stupid than smart.

00:05:53.486 --> 00:05:57.156
Well, these are the two
existential challenges

00:05:57.256 --> 00:06:01.627
that overwhelm anything
else, completely overshadow

00:06:01.727 --> 00:06:03.562
all other discussions.

00:06:03.662 --> 00:06:06.365
And their severity
and their imminence

00:06:06.465 --> 00:06:10.836
is illustrated graphically
by the famous Doomsday

00:06:10.937 --> 00:06:15.274
Clock of the Bulletin
of American Scientists.

00:06:15.374 --> 00:06:21.214
It was initiated in 1947, right
at the dawn of the Nuclear Age.

00:06:21.314 --> 00:06:28.687
In 2015, and again in 2016,
the hand was moved forward.

00:06:28.787 --> 00:06:30.957
Midnight means we're finished.

00:06:31.057 --> 00:06:35.261
The hand was moved forward
to three minutes to midnight.

00:06:35.361 --> 00:06:37.730
That's the closest it
had been to midnight

00:06:37.830 --> 00:06:42.267
since the early 1980s, when
there was a major war scare

00:06:42.367 --> 00:06:45.037
in the early Reagan years.

00:06:45.137 --> 00:06:48.507
The reasons that they gave
were the mounting threat

00:06:48.607 --> 00:06:52.444
of nuclear war and the failure
to deal with climate change.

00:06:52.545 --> 00:06:55.247
I'll quote-- what they
said is, "At the time,

00:06:55.347 --> 00:06:59.918
the probability of global
catastrophe is very high,

00:07:00.018 --> 00:07:04.856
and the actions needed to
reduce the risks of disaster

00:07:04.956 --> 00:07:07.359
must be taken very soon."

00:07:07.459 --> 00:07:10.262
That was 2016.

00:07:10.362 --> 00:07:14.200
At the outset of the
Trump term, they found--

00:07:14.300 --> 00:07:17.770
I'm quoting-- "the danger
to be even greater,

00:07:17.870 --> 00:07:20.172
the need for action
more urgent."

00:07:20.272 --> 00:07:24.210
And they moved the clock to two
and a half minutes to midnight.

00:07:24.310 --> 00:07:25.777
The clock is ticking.

00:07:25.877 --> 00:07:27.947
Global danger looms.

00:07:28.047 --> 00:07:33.352
That's the closest to
terminal disaster since 1953,

00:07:33.452 --> 00:07:39.625
when the United States and
Russia exploded their H-bombs.

00:07:39.725 --> 00:07:42.961
There is an important
difference between these two

00:07:43.061 --> 00:07:45.297
existential threats.

00:07:45.397 --> 00:07:50.803
If by some miracle, we
escape nuclear disaster--

00:07:50.903 --> 00:07:54.607
and anyone who looks
at the shocking record

00:07:54.707 --> 00:07:58.810
will realize that it's a miracle
that we've gotten this far--

00:07:58.911 --> 00:08:02.848
but if by some miracle,
we do escape, at least

00:08:02.948 --> 00:08:06.619
we know in principle
how to end the plague,

00:08:06.719 --> 00:08:09.155
get rid of the scourge.

00:08:09.255 --> 00:08:10.956
Global warming is different.

00:08:11.056 --> 00:08:12.858
It's inexorable.

00:08:12.958 --> 00:08:15.995
We might pass a point
of no return, when

00:08:16.095 --> 00:08:18.464
the damage that
we've done is simply

00:08:18.564 --> 00:08:20.699
uncontrollable, irreversible.

00:08:20.799 --> 00:08:23.702
And it might not be far off.

00:08:23.802 --> 00:08:30.275
The human species is, right
now, undertaking an experiment

00:08:30.375 --> 00:08:34.446
to determine the answer
to Ernst Mayr's question,

00:08:34.546 --> 00:08:37.917
is it better to be
smart than stupid?

00:08:38.017 --> 00:08:42.021
And what I'd like to
do now is to examine

00:08:42.121 --> 00:08:47.393
the course of the experiment,
just by picking a few dates.

00:08:47.493 --> 00:08:50.495
So let's start with today--

00:08:50.596 --> 00:08:53.465
could be any day, but
we'll start with today.

00:08:53.566 --> 00:08:57.236
If you looked at this
morning's newspapers,

00:08:57.336 --> 00:09:01.506
you see a report on how
we're dealing with the two

00:09:01.606 --> 00:09:04.075
existential crises.

00:09:04.176 --> 00:09:07.946
One on the nuclear
threat, Christopher Ford,

00:09:08.046 --> 00:09:12.285
the National Security Council
Senior Director for Weapons

00:09:12.385 --> 00:09:15.220
of Mass Destruction and
Counter-proliferation under

00:09:15.320 --> 00:09:17.490
the Trump Administration--

00:09:17.590 --> 00:09:22.794
he advises that we should
reconsider the unrealistic goal

00:09:22.894 --> 00:09:25.764
of a world without
nuclear weapons that

00:09:25.864 --> 00:09:30.069
has been advocated, among
others, by extremist

00:09:30.169 --> 00:09:35.107
peaceniks like Henry
Kissinger, George Shultz, Sam

00:09:35.207 --> 00:09:38.177
Nunn, and William Perry.

00:09:38.277 --> 00:09:41.947
And the reason for abandoning
this unrealistic goal

00:09:42.047 --> 00:09:47.319
of these utopians is Russia's
increased aggressiveness,

00:09:47.419 --> 00:09:49.788
which is, incidentally,
a charge that's

00:09:49.888 --> 00:09:52.525
dismantled quite effectively
in the current issue

00:09:52.625 --> 00:09:56.795
of a radical rag that's
worth reading now and then,

00:09:56.895 --> 00:10:01.133
Foreign Affairs, the main
establishment journal.

00:10:01.233 --> 00:10:05.871
On global warming today, this
morning, the National Snow

00:10:05.971 --> 00:10:10.208
and Ice Data Center
reports that the Arctic

00:10:10.308 --> 00:10:16.148
has less sea ice at winters
end now than ever before.

00:10:16.248 --> 00:10:20.886
That means more dark ocean,
hence more absorption

00:10:20.986 --> 00:10:22.721
of solar energy, more warming.

00:10:22.821 --> 00:10:25.123
And we're in a feedback loop.

00:10:25.223 --> 00:10:27.225
You know what that means.

00:10:27.325 --> 00:10:30.963
The mean temperature
for November

00:10:31.063 --> 00:10:33.865
was 23 degrees above normal.

00:10:33.965 --> 00:10:36.569
And at some points in the
last couple of months,

00:10:36.669 --> 00:10:40.939
it went to more than 35
degrees warmer than normal.

00:10:41.039 --> 00:10:44.176
That's today's good news.

00:10:44.276 --> 00:10:49.180
Let's go back to yesterday,
quote from The Washington Post.

00:10:49.281 --> 00:10:51.416
Water temperatures at
the surface of the Gulf

00:10:51.516 --> 00:10:56.454
of Mexico and near south
Florida are on fire.

00:10:56.554 --> 00:11:01.960
They spurred a historically warm
winter from Houston to Miami.

00:11:02.061 --> 00:11:05.197
In the Gulf, the average
sea surface temperature

00:11:05.297 --> 00:11:09.467
never fell below 73 degrees over
the winter for the first time

00:11:09.568 --> 00:11:10.836
on record.

00:11:10.936 --> 00:11:16.275
Galveston, Texas has tied or
broken an astonishing 33 record

00:11:16.375 --> 00:11:20.846
highs since November 1st,
while neighboring Houston had

00:11:20.946 --> 00:11:23.081
its warmest winter on record.

00:11:23.182 --> 00:11:26.151
Both cities have witnessed
precious few days

00:11:26.251 --> 00:11:34.026
with below normal temperatures
since late fall, and on and on.

00:11:34.126 --> 00:11:36.862
I apologize if this
is unfair, but I

00:11:36.962 --> 00:11:41.433
can't refrain from quoting
one of the comments

00:11:41.533 --> 00:11:44.636
by a reader on this news report.

00:11:44.736 --> 00:11:48.641
He says, "The Republicans
have all this under control.

00:11:48.741 --> 00:11:53.145
The plan is to have Jeff
Sessions and Ted Cruz's dad

00:11:53.245 --> 00:11:56.414
stand at the shoreline
with Bibles in hand.

00:11:56.514 --> 00:12:00.852
As the sky darkens
and the water rises,

00:12:00.952 --> 00:12:04.289
they will raise their left
hand, holding the Bible,

00:12:04.389 --> 00:12:07.425
and command the seas to settle.

00:12:07.526 --> 00:12:12.364
And if that fails, Plan
B is to run like hell,

00:12:12.464 --> 00:12:13.265
and to blame Obama."

00:12:16.569 --> 00:12:20.773
[applause]

00:12:20.873 --> 00:12:21.873
Couldn't say it better.

00:12:21.973 --> 00:12:23.209
It's a classic.

00:12:23.309 --> 00:12:28.013
And it captures the spirit
of the times very accurately.

00:12:28.113 --> 00:12:30.815
There was a second
report yesterday

00:12:30.916 --> 00:12:34.320
in the business press,
Bloomberg Businessweek.

00:12:34.420 --> 00:12:37.789
The headline was, "The
Oil Boom is Back."

00:12:37.889 --> 00:12:39.190
And I'll quote it.

00:12:39.290 --> 00:12:42.928
"The number of oil and gas rigs
drilling in the United States

00:12:43.028 --> 00:12:45.864
has almost doubled
since bottoming out

00:12:45.964 --> 00:12:50.936
at the lowest level in more
than 75 years of records.

00:12:51.036 --> 00:12:53.973
While two dozen nations
are coordinating

00:12:54.073 --> 00:12:59.344
to cut oil production and rein
in the global supply glut,

00:12:59.444 --> 00:13:02.881
US producers are moving
in the opposite direction.

00:13:02.981 --> 00:13:05.317
Over the last four
months, output

00:13:05.417 --> 00:13:09.188
increased by half a
million barrels a day.

00:13:09.288 --> 00:13:12.424
And if that rate of
expansion continues,

00:13:12.524 --> 00:13:17.228
the shale boom will break new
production records by summer.

00:13:17.329 --> 00:13:22.101
The US now produces 9
million barrels a day.

00:13:22.201 --> 00:13:25.771
We are way in the lead.

00:13:25.871 --> 00:13:31.477
This illustrates a very crucial
fact of current history.

00:13:31.577 --> 00:13:36.481
The world outside the United
States is taking steps--

00:13:36.581 --> 00:13:39.318
halting steps, but steps--

00:13:39.418 --> 00:13:45.290
towards facing the existential
challenge to survival.

00:13:45.391 --> 00:13:48.693
Meanwhile, the United
States, virtually alone,

00:13:48.793 --> 00:13:54.499
is racing towards destruction
with enthusiasm and dedication,

00:13:54.600 --> 00:13:57.536
which is quite a
remarkable fact.

00:13:57.636 --> 00:13:59.304
Now of course, the
oil industry has

00:13:59.404 --> 00:14:02.074
plenty of help in
helping and moving

00:14:02.174 --> 00:14:07.045
as quickly as it can to
destroy chances for survival.

00:14:07.145 --> 00:14:12.817
The IMF reports that the
fossil fuel industry extracts

00:14:12.918 --> 00:14:17.590
a $700 billion annual
taxpayer subsidy, which

00:14:17.690 --> 00:14:21.326
is not in the crosshairs
of Mike Mulvaney, I'm sure.

00:14:21.426 --> 00:14:24.129
And the industry
doesn't take chances.

00:14:24.229 --> 00:14:30.803
In 2016, it spent $117 million
in campaign contributions

00:14:30.903 --> 00:14:35.306
while fielding 720
lobbyists in Washington

00:14:35.407 --> 00:14:38.577
to make sure that
Congress gets the message.

00:14:38.677 --> 00:14:40.479
And apparently it does.

00:14:40.579 --> 00:14:42.814
There's a recent
Washington Post article

00:14:42.915 --> 00:14:46.484
which reports that many
Republicans in Congress

00:14:46.584 --> 00:14:50.889
do recognize the severe
threat of climate change.

00:14:50.989 --> 00:14:54.793
But they won't talk about it
because of funding pressures

00:14:54.893 --> 00:14:57.129
from the fossil fuel industry.

00:14:57.229 --> 00:15:02.233
That's particularly true
since Citizens United opened

00:15:02.333 --> 00:15:05.637
the floodgates even
wider for a flood

00:15:05.737 --> 00:15:08.306
of corporate political
funding, which

00:15:08.406 --> 00:15:11.610
means you toe the corporate
line or you're out.

00:15:11.710 --> 00:15:13.945
Well, that's yesterday.

00:15:14.045 --> 00:15:18.817
These reports are quite
typical of the daily fare.

00:15:18.917 --> 00:15:23.088
Pick almost any day,
you find similar things.

00:15:23.188 --> 00:15:26.158
Let's continue to
review the experiment

00:15:26.258 --> 00:15:28.160
that humans are undertaking.

00:15:28.260 --> 00:15:33.031
I'll just pick a few recent
dates from the last few months.

00:15:33.131 --> 00:15:35.401
So start with November 8th.

00:15:35.501 --> 00:15:39.471
That was an important day in
history for several reasons.

00:15:39.571 --> 00:15:43.041
Several events took
place on November 8th.

00:15:43.141 --> 00:15:46.245
One of them was very important.

00:15:46.345 --> 00:15:49.314
Second one was
extremely important,

00:15:49.414 --> 00:15:52.817
and the third was
absolutely astonishing.

00:15:52.917 --> 00:15:57.922
The very important one was the
election in the United States.

00:15:58.022 --> 00:16:01.126
Plenty of coverage of that, so
I don't have to talk about it.

00:16:01.226 --> 00:16:05.797
The extremely important
one took place in Morocco.

00:16:05.898 --> 00:16:11.603
In Morocco on November
8th, about 200 countries

00:16:11.703 --> 00:16:17.609
were gathering in what's
called COP22, the International

00:16:17.709 --> 00:16:22.781
Conference under
UN auspices, to try

00:16:22.881 --> 00:16:25.050
to deal with the problem
of global warming.

00:16:27.919 --> 00:16:31.390
The goal of the conference
was to put some teeth

00:16:31.490 --> 00:16:36.961
into the Paris negotiations
the year before, COP21,

00:16:37.061 --> 00:16:39.131
December 2015.

00:16:39.231 --> 00:16:43.802
That conference had aimed to
establish a verifiable treaty.

00:16:43.902 --> 00:16:46.871
But it couldn't do
it for one reason--

00:16:46.971 --> 00:16:48.440
the Republican
Congress would not

00:16:48.540 --> 00:16:51.176
accept any binding commitments.

00:16:51.276 --> 00:16:55.247
So therefore, the world had
to settle for something less,

